Key takeaways.

A hash map converts a key to a bucket index via a hash function — the index equals the hash of the key modulo the table size. That arithmetic is why lookup is constant time.

Collisions happen when two keys land in the same bucket. Chaining resolves them with a short list per bucket. With a good hash function and a healthy load factor, chains stay length one.

All core operations — get, put, delete, contains — are constant time on average. Treat them as constant time in practice. A hash set is a hash map without values — constant-time membership, deduplication, and set algebra.

Keys must be hashable — immutable types only. The four canonical patterns are: frequency counting with Counter, grouping with a default-dict of lists, complement lookup for pair-finding, and sliding window with a last-seen index map. Use a tree map when you need sorted key order; use a plain hash map when you just need fast lookup.
